[For the references included in the above assessment, please refer to the source URL.

The relatively long time-span between the start of the Turkish LSD event (reportedly, 6 Aug 2013) and the date of the pre-confirmation of the event (13 Sep 2013), with allergy initially suspected, should not surprise. On 20 Aug 1989, an experienced, well-equipped, knowledgeable veterinary practitioner was called upon a 4-year-old, lactating dairy cow on a dairy farm in southern Israel, the owner complaining about decreased milk production. He initially diagnosed it as a case of allergy, then (24 Aug 1989) allergy and urticaria. The cow eventually deteriorated to "severe urticaria, edema of lungs and legs" (15 Sep 1989). By that day, several similar cases began to appear on the same and neighbouring farms. This eventually led the attending practitioner to involve experts; soon, the preliminary diagnosis of the 1st occurrence in Israel of an exotic, unfamiliar cattle disease, lumpy skin disease, was established. Electron microscopy was followed by other laboratory means. The outbreak was limited to one village (63 clinical cases out of a susceptible population of 633 cows, negligible mortality). The outbreak was eventually eradicated by stamping out on 29 Sep 1989. The event may serve as another reminder to veterinary clinicians about their ever-required alertness and awareness, as well as about the potential advantage of timely call upon specialists, if available, when addressing a "mystery" disease.

Regarding the vaccines applied during 2013 for cattle vaccination in Israel, subscribers are reminded that general, countrywide vaccination of cattle has become operational there since March 2013 and the incidence of disease has dropped abruptly, though sporadic cases are still being seen. Two live attenuated vaccines have been applied, namely the (10-fold fortified) sheep pox vaccine "POX-10," manufactured by JOVAC, and the Neethling lumpy skin vaccine, manufactured by OBP. Investigations into the safety and efficacy of both vaccines under field conditions have been undertaken cooperatively by the State Veterinary Services, the Koret School of Veterinary Medicine, and the "Hachaklait" Clinical Veterinary Services. Preliminary results are expected.

A media report of LSD in Turkey, including a picture of a local diseased animal with the typical lesions (http://tinyurl.com/pp33dwj), was published by ProMED-mail on 31 Aug 2013.

Turkey's immediate notification on LSD was submitted to the OIE on 17 Sep 2013. It indicated "vaccination in response to the outbreak" as "a measure to be applied." Information on the applied vaccination (and, if possible, on the vaccine applied) is anticipated in the due follow-up reports. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/8AUp.]
